CHAPTER 8.
8. DATABASE DESIGN


Database design defines how data is structured, stored, accessed, and managed within a system. In the PG Accommodation Finder project, the database design deviates from traditional server-based database architectures due to the frontend-only nature of the application. Instead of using a centralized database server, the system adopts a client-side data persistence approach using browser localStorage and static JSON files.
This chapter explains the rationale behind the chosen data storage strategy, the logical data models, data structures used, and the flow of data persistence within the application.

8.1 Data Storage Approach
The PG Accommodation Finder application is designed without backend or server-side components. As a result, all data storage and retrieval operations are performed on the client side. The system uses a hybrid data storage strategy consisting of static JSON files for initial data loading and browser localStorage for runtime persistence.
Static JSON files are used to store predefined PG accommodation listings that are loaded when the application initializes. Browser localStorage is used to persist dynamic data such as user authentication details, booking requests, reviews, and user profiles. This approach ensures that data remains available across page reloads within the same browser environment.
While this method is not suitable for large-scale production systems, it is effective for academic projects, prototypes, and frontend-focused implementations.

8.2 Logical Data Model
The logical data model represents the structure of data entities and their relationships without considering physical storage mechanisms. The primary data entities in the system include Users, PG Listings, Bookings, and Reviews.
Each entity is designed to reflect real-world accommodation processes while maintaining simplicity and clarity.

8.3 Entity Description and Attributes
8.3.1 User Entity
The User entity represents all individuals interacting with the system. Users are classified into students/professionals and PG owners based on their role.
Each user record contains essential attributes such as unique user identifier, name, email address, phone number, role type, and authentication status. For students and professionals, booking history is associated with the user profile. For PG owners, listed properties and received booking requests are linked to the user.
User data is stored securely in localStorage and retrieved upon login to maintain session continuity.

8.3.2 PG Listing Entity
The PG Listing entity represents accommodation properties available for booking. Each listing contains property-specific information such as PG name, location, address, price, available rooms, gender preference, amenities, description, owner details, and verification status.
Listings are initially loaded from a static JSON file and then managed dynamically during runtime. Owners can add, update, or remove listings through the dashboard interface, with changes reflected in localStorage.

8.3.3 Booking Entity
The Booking entity captures all booking requests submitted by users. Each booking record includes a unique booking ID, associated PG ID, user ID, move-in date, booking status, and optional user message.
Booking status values include pending, approved, and rejected. Owners update booking statuses through the dashboard, and corresponding changes are reflected in the user’s booking history.

8.3.4 Review Entity
The Review entity stores user feedback for PG accommodations. Each review includes the reviewer’s user ID, PG ID, star rating, review comment, and submission date.
Reviews are displayed publicly on PG detail pages and contribute to the calculation of average ratings. All review data is stored persistently in localStorage.

8.4 Entity Relationship Overview
The relationships between entities define how different data components interact logically within the system.
A user can submit multiple booking requests, but each booking is associated with only one PG listing. A PG listing can receive multiple booking requests from different users. Similarly, users can submit multiple reviews, and each PG listing can have multiple associated reviews.

8.5 Entity Relationship Diagram (ER Diagram)
The following diagram illustrates the logical relationships between major entities in the system.
User
 ├── userId
 ├── name
 ├── email
 ├── phone
 ├── role
 │
 │ 1
 │
 │
