 ├── rating
 ├── comment
This ER diagram reflects a simplified but effective data model suitable for frontend-based applications.

8.6 Physical Data Representation
Since no traditional database is used, physical data representation is achieved using JSON objects stored in localStorage.
Sample PG Listing Structure
{
  "pgId": 101,
  "name": "Green View PG",
  "location": "Bangalore",
  "address": "BTM Layout",
  "price": 12000,
  "availableRooms": 3,
  "gender": "Boys",
  "amenities": ["WiFi", "Food", "Laundry"],
  "ownerId": 201,
  "rating": 4.5
}
Sample Booking Structure
{
  "bookingId": "BKG123",
  "userId": 301,
  "pgId": 101,
  "moveInDate": "2024-06-01",
  "status": "Pending",
  "message": "Looking for immediate move-in"
}
Sample Review Structure
{
  "reviewId": "RV501",
  "userId": 301,
  "pgId": 101,
  "rating": 5,
  "comment": "Clean rooms and good food",
  "date": "2024-05-20"
}
These structures ensure consistency and ease of manipulation within JavaScript.

8.7 Data Flow and Persistence Mechanism
When a user performs an action such as registering, booking a PG, or submitting a review, the corresponding data object is created or updated within the application state managed by the Context API. The updated state is then serialized and stored in localStorage.
On application reload, stored data is retrieved from localStorage and rehydrated into the application state, ensuring continuity of user sessions and stored records.

8.8 Data Security and Limitations
Client-side storage offers simplicity but has inherent limitations. Data stored in localStorage is device-specific and lacks encryption by default. The system does not handle concurrent users or cross-device synchronization.
These limitations are acceptable within the academic scope of the project. In future implementations, backend databases and authentication services can replace client-side storage to enhance security and scalability.






9. IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS
This chapter describes the practical implementation of the PG Accommodation Finder application. It explains how the system architecture and design decisions discussed in previous chapters were translated into a working software solution. The chapter focuses on component implementation, routing logic, state management, data persistence, and user interaction handling.
The implementation strictly follows a frontend-only approach using modern web development technologies, ensuring clarity, modularity, and maintainability.

9.1 Project Structure and Organization
The project follows a well-structured and modular folder organization to ensure readability and ease of maintenance. The source code is divided into logical directories based on functionality.
The main project structure includes folders for components, pages, context, assets, and utility files. Shared UI components such as navigation bars, cards, and filters are placed in a common components directory to encourage reuse. Page-level components such as Home, Listings, PG Details, Dashboard, and Profile are separated to maintain clear responsibility boundaries.
This structured organization simplifies debugging, testing, and future enhancements.

9.2 Application Entry Point and Initialization
The application execution begins from the main entry file, where the React application is mounted to the browser DOM. The root component wraps the entire application with routing and global state providers.
The Context API provider initializes global state values such as user authentication status, PG listings, bookings, and reviews. On application startup, data stored in localStorage is retrieved and injected into the state to restore previous user sessions.
This initialization ensures that user data persists across page reloads and browser sessions.

9.3 Routing and Navigation Implementation
Client-side routing is implemented using React Router DOM. Routes are defined for public pages such as Home and Listings, as well as protected pages such as Profile and Owner Dashboard.
Role-based route protection is implemented by checking authentication status and user role before rendering protected components. Unauthorized users attempting to access restricted pages are redirected to the login page.
Dynamic routing is used for PG detail pages, where each listing is accessed using a unique PG identifier in the URL. This approach enables clean URLs and direct access to individual PG information pages.

9.4 State Management Using Context API
Global state management is implemented using the React Context API to avoid prop drilling and ensure consistent data access across components.
A centralized context manages multiple state variables, including user details, authentication status, PG listings, booking records, and reviews. Context functions handle operations such as login, logout, booking submission, booking status updates, and review addition.
State updates trigger automatic UI re-rendering, ensuring that changes are immediately reflected throughout the application.

9.5 Implementation of User Authentication
User authentication is implemented using a simple role-based mechanism suitable for a frontend-only system. During registration, user details such as name, email, phone number, role, and password are captured and stored in localStorage.
During login, entered credentials are validated against stored user records. Upon successful authentication, user session details are stored in localStorage and reflected in the global state.
Logout functionality clears session data from localStorage and resets authentication state, preventing unauthorized access.

9.6 PG Listing Implementation
PG listings are initially loaded from a static JSON file containing predefined accommodation data. This data includes property details such as name, location, price, amenities, and availability.
Owners can add new PG listings through structured forms. Submitted listing data is validated and then appended to the existing listings stored in localStorage. Editing and deletion functionalities allow owners to update listing details dynamically.
Changes made by owners are immediately reflected in the listings page due to centralized state management.

9.7 Search and Filter Functionality
The search functionality allows users to search PG listings by property name or location using a keyword-based approach. Filtering options are implemented using controlled form inputs that update filter state variables.
Filters such as budget range, gender preference, and amenities work in combination to refine displayed results. Sorting options allow users to reorder listings based on price or rating.
The filtered results are computed dynamically within the component render cycle, ensuring fast response without additional data fetching.

9.8 Booking System Implementation
The booking system enables authenticated users to submit booking requests from PG detail pages. Booking forms capture user details, preferred move-in date, and optional messages.
Upon submission, a booking object is created with a unique booking identifier and stored in localStorage. The booking status is initially set to “Pending”.
PG owners can view booking requests associated with their properties through the dashboard. Owners can approve or reject requests, which updates booking status and available room count accordingly.

9.9 Review and Rating Module Implementation
The review module allows authenticated users to submit ratings and textual feedback for PG accommodations. Rating values are restricted to a defined range to maintain consistency.
Submitted reviews are associated with the respective PG identifier and stored in localStorage. The system calculates average ratings dynamically based on submitted reviews.
Reviews are displayed on PG detail pages in chronological order, enhancing transparency and trust.

9.10 Owner Dashboard Implementation
The owner dashboard serves as a centralized management interface for PG owners. It displays summary statistics such as total listings, pending bookings, approved bookings, and rejected bookings.
Tabbed navigation separates listing management and booking management functionalities. Owners can perform CRUD operations on listings and manage booking requests efficiently.
This dashboard significantly reduces administrative overhead for property owners.

9.11 User Profile Module Implementation
The user profile module allows students and professionals to view and manage their personal information. Editable profile forms enable users to update contact details.
The booking history section displays all booking requests submitted by the user along with their current status. Links allow users to navigate to PG details directly from booking records.
This module improves user engagement and system transparency.

9.12 Data Persistence Using Local Storage
All dynamic data is persisted using the browser localStorage API. Whenever state changes occur, updated data is serialized and saved to localStorage.
On application reload, stored data is retrieved and used to rehydrate the application state. This mechanism ensures continuity of user sessions and stored records.
While localStorage has limitations, it effectively supports the academic scope of the project.

9.13 Error Handling and Validation
Form-level validation ensures that required fields are filled and valid data is entered. Error messages provide clear feedback to users in case of invalid input.
Basic error handling mechanisms prevent application crashes due to undefined data or invalid state transitions.

9.14 Performance and Optimization Considerations
Reusable components and conditional rendering minimize unnecessary UI updates. Efficient state management reduces re-render cycles.
Optimized asset loading and lightweight architecture ensure fast application performance across devices.












10. TESTING
Testing is a critical phase in the software development lifecycle that ensures the application functions correctly, reliably, and as intended. The primary objective of testing the PG Accommodation Finder application is to identify defects, validate functional requirements, and ensure a smooth user experience across different usage scenarios.
Since the project follows a frontend-only architecture, testing primarily focuses on functional validation, user interface behavior, data consistency, and interaction workflows rather than server-side performance or security testing.

10.1 Objectives of Testing
The testing process aims to verify that each module of the application performs according to the specified requirements. It ensures that user actions result in correct system responses and that the application handles both valid and invalid inputs gracefully.
Testing also aims to validate navigation flow, state management consistency, data persistence using localStorage, and compatibility across devices and browsers. By identifying and fixing issues early, testing improves system reliability and user confidence.

10.2 Testing Strategy
A systematic testing strategy is adopted to ensure complete coverage of application functionality. The strategy includes manual testing of all modules and interaction flows, as the project is frontend-focused and UI-driven.
The testing approach follows a modular structure, where individual components are tested independently before validating integrated workflows such as booking and review submission. Special attention is given to edge cases, incorrect user inputs, and authorization-based access control.

10.3 Types of Testing Performed
10.3.1 Unit Testing
Unit testing focuses on validating individual components and functions in isolation. Each React component is tested to ensure it renders correctly and responds appropriately to user interactions.
Examples include testing form input components, PG card rendering, filter selection behavior, and button click handlers. Unit testing ensures that component-level logic is error-free before integration.

10.3.2 Integration Testing
Integration testing verifies the interaction between multiple components and modules. This type of testing ensures that data flows correctly across components through the Context API.
Key integration scenarios include navigation between pages, passing PG identifiers from listings to detail pages, and synchronizing booking status updates across user and owner dashboards. Successful integration testing confirms that modules work cohesively as a single system.

10.3.3 Functional Testing
Functional testing validates the application against its functional requirements. Each feature described in the project scope is tested using real-world user scenarios.
Examples include user registration, login authentication, PG search and filtering, booking request submission, booking approval or rejection, and review posting. Functional testing ensures that all system features operate correctly and deliver expected outputs.

10.3.4 User Interface Testing
User interface testing ensures that all UI elements display correctly and maintain consistency across different screen sizes and devices. Layout alignment, font readability, button responsiveness, and navigation clarity are evaluated.
Responsive design behavior is tested on desktops, tablets, and mobile devices to ensure usability remains consistent. UI testing also verifies accessibility aspects such as form labels, input validation messages, and visual feedback.

10.3.5 Data Persistence Testing
Since the application relies on browser localStorage for data persistence, testing focuses on validating correct data storage and retrieval.
Scenarios include verifying session persistence after page reloads, ensuring booking data is retained correctly, and confirming review data remains available across sessions. Data consistency testing ensures that stored data reflects the current application state accurately.

10.3.6 Security and Authorization Testing
Basic security testing is performed to validate role-based access control. Unauthorized users are restricted from accessing protected pages such as the owner dashboard and user profile.
Testing confirms that students cannot access owner functionalities and that guest users cannot submit booking requests or reviews. Although advanced security mechanisms are not implemented due to frontend-only scope, basic authorization logic is thoroughly validated.

10.4 Test Environment
Testing is conducted in a controlled development environment using modern web browsers. The application is tested on multiple browsers to ensure compatibility and consistent behavior.
Different device viewports are simulated using browser developer tools to test responsiveness. LocalStorage data is cleared and reset frequently to validate system behavior under fresh and repeated usage conditions.

10.5 Test Cases
10.5.1 Authentication Module Test Cases
User registration is tested with valid and invalid input data to ensure form validation works correctly. Login functionality is tested with correct and incorrect credentials to verify authentication logic.
Logout functionality is tested to ensure session data is cleared and access to protected routes is revoked.

10.5.2 PG Listing and Search Test Cases
PG listing display is tested to ensure all properties load correctly from static data and localStorage. Search functionality is tested using different keywords to validate matching behavior.
Filter options are tested individually and in combination to ensure accurate result refinement. Sorting options are tested to confirm correct ordering of listings.

10.5.3 Booking Module Test Cases
Booking request submission is tested with valid data to ensure successful storage and confirmation display. Attempting to book without authentication is tested to confirm redirection to the login page.
Booking status updates by owners are tested to ensure changes are reflected in both owner and user views. Available room count updates are validated after booking approval.

10.5.4 Review and Rating Test Cases
Review submission is tested to ensure only authenticated users can post reviews. Rating value constraints are validated to prevent invalid ratings.
Average rating calculation is tested to ensure accuracy after multiple reviews. Review display order and content consistency are verified.

10.5.5 Profile and Dashboard Test Cases
User profile updates are tested to ensure changes are stored and reflected correctly. Booking history display is validated for accuracy and completeness.
Owner dashboard functionalities such as listing creation, editing, deletion, and booking management are tested to ensure smooth operation.

10.6 Test Results and Observations
All major functional modules of the PG Accommodation Finder application were tested successfully. The application demonstrated stable behavior across different browsers and devices.
Minor UI alignment issues were identified during initial testing and corrected. Data persistence using localStorage was found to be reliable within the same browser environment. Role-based access control functioned as expected.
No critical functional defects were observed after final testing.

10.7 Limitations of Testing
Due to the frontend-only nature of the project, certain types of testing such as server load testing, database performance testing, and penetration testing were not applicable.
Additionally, localStorage-based persistence limits testing scenarios related to multi-user concurrency and cross-device synchronization.





